\begin_layout Standard
The quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{1+j}\det A_{\backslash1,j}$
\end_inset

 of formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) are called 
\series bold
cofactors
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
cofactor
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 More generally, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{i+j}\det A_{\backslash i,j}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-cofactor of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Cofactors can be computed for any row-column combination.
 Using the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-cofactor, recursion (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:determinant_row_1_expansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be rewritten 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det A=A_{1,1}C_{1,1}+A_{1,2}C_{1,2}+\cdots+A_{1,n}C_{1,n}.\label{eq:determinant_cofactors}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

While more succinct, this presentation hides the details of the calculation.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 may be an involved calcuation itself.
\end_layout

