\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Casting the equation in terms of matrices and solving:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
3 & 7 & 1\end{array}\right]+b\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
9 & 6 & 2\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
8 & 4 & 5\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
3a+9b\  & 7a+6b\  & a+2b\end{array}\right] & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
8 & 4 & 5\end{array}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For these two row matrices to be equal corresponding entries must be equal.
 That is, the simultaneous equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
3a+9b & =8\\
7a+6b & =4\\
a+2b & =5
\end{align*}

\end_inset

must all be true.
 The second and third equations can be solved (as a system) by elimination,
 for example.
 The second equation minus 3 times the third equation yields 
\begin_inset Formula $4a=-11$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{-11}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting into the third equation yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{-11}{4}+2b=5$
\end_inset

 which means 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\frac{31}{8}$
\end_inset

.
 These values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 constitute the only simultaneous solution of the second and third equations.
 Substituting into the first equation yields 
\begin_inset Formula $3\left(\frac{-11}{4}\right)+9\left(\frac{31}{8}\right)=8$
\end_inset

 which can be confirmed FALSE! Therefore there is no solution.
 There is no way to write the third row of the 
